Take a look at [testcontainers][1], which allows you to spin up infrastructure needed for tests (things like databases, or in your case a fake gcs server)


  [1]: https://www.testcontainers.org/test_framework_integration/junit_5/

Start by adding the necessary maven dependencies:

    &lt;properties&gt;
        &lt;testcontainers.version&gt;1.16.4&lt;/testcontainers.version&gt;
    &lt;/properties&gt;
    
    &lt;dependency&gt;
        &lt;groupId&gt;org.testcontainers&lt;/groupId&gt;
        &lt;artifactId&gt;junit-jupiter&lt;/artifactId&gt;
        &lt;version&gt;${testcontainers.version}&lt;/version&gt;
        &lt;scope&gt;test&lt;/scope&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;

Then use the GenericContainer to create a GCS container, specifying the docker image name and version:

    @Testcontainers
    class GcsIntegrationTest {
    
        // will be shared between test methods
        @Container
        private static final GenericContainer&lt;?&gt; GCS_CONTAINER = new GenericContainer&lt;&gt;(DockerImageName.parse(&quot;fsouza/fake-gcs-server:1.33.1&quot;))
            .withExposedPorts(4443)
            .withClasspathResourceMapping(&quot;gcs/data&quot;, &quot;/data&quot;, BindMode.READ_ONLY)
    
        @Test
        void test() {
            assertTrue(GCS_CONTAINER.isRunning());
            // more assertions
        }
    }

The &#39;withClasspathResourceMapping&#39; part can be used to specify some test data you wish to mount inside the container for the test: https://github.com/fsouza/fake-gcs-server#preload-data

